{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17412846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17412846"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261081"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538421"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16184"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261081"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:50:23+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":3,"questionsAnswered":2,"marksTotal":2,"marksAttainable":2,"marksAttempted":2,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T07:41:47+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"16184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16184"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.94,0.01,0.01,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64249"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16184"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49681"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4340"},{"type":"tags","id":"4347"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21135"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38075"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64249"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit at eight weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. She works as an accountant and lives with her partner. She asks about the safety of having \u0027just one glass of wine\u0027 at her friend\u0027s upcoming wedding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 22 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice regarding alcohol consumption during pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete abstinence is recommended","Light drinking in late pregnancy is safe","Red wine is safer than other forms of alcohol","Occasional drinking after the first trimester is safe","One standard drink per day is safe"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe safest approach to alcohol consumption during pregnancy is complete abstinence. No safe level of alcohol consumption during pregnancy has been established, and alcohol can affect fetal development throughout pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete abstinence\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended by health authorities worldwide because alcohol readily crosses the placenta and can cause a range of adverse effects on fetal development, particularly neurodevelopment. This recommendation extends to women who are planning pregnancy or who might be pregnant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOne standard drink per day\u003C/strong\u003E is not safe during pregnancy. Even small amounts of alcohol can potentially harm the developing fetus, and the effects can vary between individuals due to genetic and metabolic differences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed wine\u003C/strong\u003E being safer than other forms of alcohol is a common misconception. All types of alcoholic beverages can cause fetal harm as it is the ethanol itself that is toxic to the developing fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOccasional drinking after the first trimester\u003C/strong\u003E is not safe. While the first trimester is a particularly vulnerable period for organ development, the fetal brain continues to develop throughout pregnancy and can be affected by alcohol at any stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELight drinking in late pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is not safe. The fetal brain continues to develop in the third trimester and is vulnerable to alcohol exposure throughout pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFetal Alcohol Spectrum Disorder (FASD) encompasses a range of physical, mental, behavioural, and learning disabilities that can occur in individuals who were exposed to alcohol before birth. These effects are irreversible and can have lifelong impacts on the affected individual.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["There is no known safe level of alcohol consumption during pregnancy.","Alcohol exposure during pregnancy can cause fetal alcohol spectrum disorder with lifelong neurodevelopmental impacts.","Complete abstinence from alcohol is recommended for all pregnant women and those planning pregnancy."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Substance use in pregnancy [Internet]. East Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2020 [cited 2024 Nov 22]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Substance-Use-Pregnancy.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49681"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16184"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49681"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T10:31:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T10:32:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64249"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount"